{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8f384149-706f-488b-ac59-69c5df902b48","content":"The .NET Android SDK **doesn't use `JAVA_HOME`** by default. It has its own JDK discovery logic and on macOS looks for the **Microsoft OpenJDK** that ships with the workload — not Adoptium.\n\n**Two fixes (pick one):**\n\n**1. Tell MSBuild where your JDK is:**\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=\"$JAVA_HOME\"\n```\nOr permanently in your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory Condition=\"'$(JavaSdkDirectory)' == ''\">$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**2. Install the Microsoft OpenJDK that the workload expects:**\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui\n```\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 to the path the build system auto-discovers.\n\n**Option 2 is the path of least resistance** — it \"just works\" without extra configuration.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0a21f0d5-a1ad-4713-9a75-bb56a5e94c24","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about common .NET MAUI Android + Java issues:\n\n1. .NET MAUI Android builds use Java (for Android SDK tools, D8/R8, etc.)\n2. The key issue is likely that .NET 8+ MAUI requires JDK 17, but there can be path issues on macOS specifically.\n\nOn macOS, the common issue with Adoptium Temurin JDK is the **JAVA_HOME path**. Adoptium installs to `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but .NET MAUI's build system (specifically the `<JavaSdkDirectory>` MSBuild property) needs to find it correctly.\n\n\nThe real problem is likely that while JAVA_HOME is set correctly, the .NET Android build tasks don't always respect it the same way—they look for Java in specific hardcoded locations, and on macOS with Adoptium, there's often a mismatch between where the environment variable points and where MSBuild actually searches.\n\nThe actual issue is probably that .NET MAUI on macOS preferentially looks for the Microsoft OpenJDK distribution rather than Adoptium, so even though they have JDK 17 installed, it's the wrong vendor. The solution would be either installing Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 or explicitly setting the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property to point to their Adoptium installation.\n\nWithout knowing the exact error message, I'm thinking through the most common Java-related failures they might be hitting. The most common culprit on macOS is that the Android workload installs Microsoft's OpenJDK to a specific location, and the build system prefers that over JAVA_HOME, so even if Adoptium is set up correctly, there's a path conflict or the build isn't finding the bundled JDK where it expects it. The real issue is probably that MSBuild doesn't actually consult JAVA_HOME when building Android projects—the .NET SDK has its own hardcoded search paths on macOS, so I should either pass the Java directory explicitly via a build property or add it to the project file. Let me think through what the most common culprit actually is here. I think I have a solid answer here without needing to dig deeper into the codebase.","outputTokens":1846,"requestId":"1031:1E23:259877:2C0A30:69FD3401"},"id":"a63921a6-0a3a-4df7-b08c-2e17c29331f6","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:53:59.893Z","parentId":"e5dbd05d-4748-456e-bc4b-779ac60b220b"}
